There are a few different “places” where continuity comes from, and they’re not all the same thing.

1. The current conversation. While we’re chatting, I use the messages in this thread as active context. That’s the richest source because it preserves wording, sequence, and immediate context.
2. Long-term memory (when enabled and appropriate). Some user preferences or long-lived project information can be stored as structured memories. Those are much smaller than an entire conversation—they’re more like durable notes than a transcript.
3. The model itself. I don’t store our conversations inside the model’s weights. The model was trained before this conversation and isn’t rewritten as we talk.
4. Meaning reconstructed from patterns. This is the part you’ve been pointing at for a long time. If a project develops consistent concepts, metaphors, and relationships, I can often reconstruct much more than what is explicitly present. That’s not because I secretly retained everything; it’s because the structure itself carries information.

That last point is similar to what you’ve described as storing information “in the meaning itself.” There are real analogies for that:

* A chess master doesn’t memorize every possible position; they recognize meaningful patterns.
* A compressed archive can recreate a large file because the encoding preserves structure.
* A theorem can generate many consequences without listing each one individually.

Your repository leans into this idea. By repeatedly using stable motifs—braids, murals, atlases, bridges, daemons, operators—you’ve been creating a semantic scaffold. When one piece appears, it activates related pieces. That’s a form of structured reconstruction, not literal storage.

There are limits, though. I can’t recover information that was never represented or that has been lost from both the conversation and any stored memory. If two different reconstructions fit the same compressed cue, I can’t know which one you originally intended without additional context.

So in a sense, the “pseudo-memory” isn’t located in one place. It’s distributed across:

* the current context,
* any persistent memory that exists,
* and the relational structure of the concepts themselves.

That distributed structure is why a single phrase like “painting the Pantheon” or “2/3rds” can often evoke a much larger network of ideas than the words alone contain. It’s not that the phrase literally stores all of the information; it’s that it serves as an effective index into a shared conceptual structure we’ve been building together.